data: # Lesson 19: Dim an RGB LED from web

## 1 Overview

In this lesson you will learn how to control the brightness of each colour of an RGB LED. This lesson is very similar with the previous one, but this time we have a RGB LED, inside which there are 3 LEDs: red, green and blue.
Below, you can find a visual representation of the connections:

## 4 Code

The code for this lesson is similar with the one from the previous lesson, but we will use three sliders, one for each colour.

At the beginning of the code we will import the necessary modules from the **bottle** library and the **Rpi.GPIO** library as **GPIO**. Next, we will set the **GPIO** in **BOARD** mode, declare the pins used by the RGB Led and set them as OUTPUT. For those pins we will create PWM instances and initialize those instances with a duty cycle of **0**.

Next, we have to deal with the routes for our user interface. For that, we need a route to the default location, which is â/â. For this route we have created a function that uses **template** to send the **index.html** page to the default location.

For each Led we have a route and a function associated. When one of the sliders is moved, the state will be sent to the server and the corresponding function will be called. In each function we have a request to the web page that will send the state of the slider. According to which slider was moved, the corresponding function will modify the duty cycle of the specified Led with the value given of the slider. In the end of each function will be a instruction for sending an OK message.

The code will end with a **run** call that will listen to HTTP requests on all interfaces. This **run** is located inside a **try-except** block so that when we will interrupt the connection, we can clean the used GPIO ports.

The HTML page is similar with the one from the previous lesson, the only difference is that this time we will have three sliders. In the body of the page we need to create three sliders and besides each slider will be a block that displays the current state of the slider (which is also the brightness of the LED).

The JavaScript part is also multipled by 3. We will use the **.on()** method, with the **change** event association, three times and we will proceed the same as in the previous lesson.

"""
*   Credits: www.plusivo.com
*
*   Lesson 19: Dim an RGB LED from web
*
*   The code below is created for the lesson "Dim an RGB LED from
*   web", where we will define a slider for each colour of the
*   RGB LED and controlling the individual brightnesses.
*
*   More information about can be found in the guide.
*
"""

#import the necessary modules from the bottle library
from bottle import route, run, template, request
#we will import the RPi.GPIO library with the name of GPIO
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

#we will set the pin numbering to the GPIO.BOARD numbering
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)

#define the pins used by the Led
red = 8
green = 10
blue = 12

#set the pins used by the Led as OUTPUT
GPIO.setup(red, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(green, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(blue, GPIO.OUT)

#we will create three PWM instances for the pins set as OUTPUT
redPIN = GPIO.PWM(red, 1000)
greenPIN = GPIO.PWM(green, 1000)
bluePIN = GPIO.PWM(blue, 1000)

#we will start the PWM with a duty cycle of 0
redPIN.start(0)
greenPIN.start(0)
bluePIN.start(0)

#define the route for the main page
@route('/')
def index():
    #at the '/' route we will return the index.html
    #template that is in the views folder
    return template('index.html')

@route('/redFunction', method = 'POST')
def red_function():
    #request data from web page
    state1 = int(request.POST.get('state1'))

    #change the duty cycle with the value of the slider
    redPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(state1)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/greenFunction', method = 'POST')
def green_function():
    #request data from web page
    state2 = int(request.POST.get('state2'))

    #change the duty cycle with the value of the slider
    greenPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(state2)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

@route('/blueFunction', method = 'POST')
def blue_function():
    #request data from web page
    state3 = int(request.POST.get('state3'))

    #change the duty cycle with the value of the slider
    bluePIN.ChangeDutyCycle(state3)

    #send a message to the user
    return 'ok'

try:
    #we will run the app on port 5000
    run(host = '0.0.0.0', port = '5000')

except KeyboardInterrupt:
    pass

#clean the used ports
GPIO.cleanup()
